{{unsourced|date=April 2017}}
'''Cross-resistance''' is the [[Drug tolerance|tolerance]] to a usually [[toxic substance]] as a result of exposure to a similarly acting substance. It is a phenomenon affecting e.g. [[pesticide]]s and [[antibiotic]]s. As an example [[rifabutin]] and [[rifampin]] cross react in the treatment of tuberculosis. This sort of resistance is also seen against drugs involved with the treatment of HIV. Drugs ending  with "- ine" and "-inavir" are the most common.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}

